Communism Makes a Comeback in Russia
Moscow—More than a year ago, during a sabbatical from the American university where I was teaching, I returned to my hometown, Moscow.
My destination was not a stronghold of free speech.
Yet, some freedoms still remained in this place.
Opposition leader Alexei Navalny once traveled across the country in an attempt to gain support from politicians not controlled by the Kremlin.
Mass protests erupted.
Independent non-governmental organizations operate domestically.
Journalists and analysts are not necessarily following the Kremlin's line.
Meanwhile, the Communist Party is widely seen as a relic of the past.
Since then, Navalny has been imprisoned, and the protests he initiated have been suppressed.
Its anti-corruption foundation was outlawed as "extremist," and its members are being exiled or investigated.
Nearly every day, journalists, media organizations, human rights advocates, or independent institutions are added to the "foreign agents" list — — and even worse — — labeled as "unwanted individuals."
Last year, Russia fell into a non-free state, though not far away, but very intense.
For example, a law designating foreign agents was enacted in 2012, aiming to undermine or discredit institutions or individuals engaged in "political activities" while simultaneously receiving funding from abroad.
However, the application of this law has become increasingly arbitrary, to the point that even retweeting now serves as a reason to be labeled a foreign agent.
Being labeled as an "unwanted individual" can lead to complete prohibition.
Just this year alone, a record 101 entities were added to the foreign agents list.
The cumulative total of 359 includes 88 media-related organizations and individuals.
According to the Russian government, the above-mentioned "agents" must be included on the list because they "influence the country's politics."
But of course, the core goal of journalism and propaganda work is to influence politics.
This is precisely the problem: although President Vladimir Putin has positioned himself to continue controlling Russian politics in the foreseeable future, he views criticism as a threat to his survival.
Despite enduring all this silence and persecution, the only true opposition group that has survived within the Kremlin is an unlikely one — the Communist Party.
This is largely due to Navalny's "smart voting" strategy — encouraging people to support those most likely to defeat candidates backed by the Kremlin — and the Communist Party performed very strongly in last month's parliamentary and regional elections.
Official data shows that Communist Party candidates won 18.9% of the vote in the State Duma (parliament), while the Kremlin-backed United Russia party received nearly 49.8%.
However, the Communists refused to accept this result, insisting that the voting results were manipulated.
In fact, some experts estimate that they should have received about 30% of the votes, while the United Russia party should have received about 35%.
For many Russians, the communists now seem more respected than Putin.
But they are no longer the original communists.
Not only do they not deny the pleasures of the world, but the party members are even wearing fur coats, enthusiastic about traveling abroad, driving foreign cars, and using social media.
Some of them are millionaires — for example, the charming agriculture chief Pavel Grudinin (who was banned from participating in last month's election).
Although the party is still led by Gennady Zyuganov, who is 77 years old, it is increasingly influenced and supported by younger members.
Take Nikolai Bondarenko as an example.
Known as "Red Navalny," 36-year-old Bondarenko severely criticized the poorly designed pension reform of 2018.
Not long ago, when a regional minister said Russians should be able to "eat better" with a monthly salary of just 3,500 rubles (about $50), Bondarenko recorded his efforts to prove the man wrong on his own YouTube channel.
Although threatened with a ban from running for office, Bondarenko was still allowed to participate in the recent State Duma elections.
Although he received support from Navalny's "smart voting" system, he still lost to the United Russia candidate.
But his potential should not be overlooked: he recently drafted a title for a protest, accusing "the state and government" of taking over United Russia.
Then there is 43-year-old Anastasia Yudanova.
Like Bondarenko, she astonishingly lost the last election.
But she remains — and is becoming increasingly — popular.
Thanks to the "smart voting" system, another rising star, the elegant Ekaterina Engalicheva, was elected to the Moscow City Duma in 2019.
Ironically, the modernization of the Communist Party reflects people's longing for the past: in 1917, Lenin's Bolsheviks promised justice and equality, and although the state that realized these ideals was strict, it was not lacking in fairness and compassion.
Moreover, like the liberal Navalny, today's Communist Party represents a predictable and consistent vision, under which one person's whims will not affect everyone.
It is precisely based on this logic that all opponents of the Kremlin are increasingly uniting: forming a "United Russia" capable of confronting Putin's United Russia Party.
This situation is not limited to Russia.
In the recent parliamentary elections in the Czech Republic, Andrej Babiš — also known as the Czech Donald Trump — failed to be re-elected as prime minister, as the opposition alliance set aside their ideological differences and formed a united coalition, with its leader Petr Fiala likely to lead a new government alongside another opposition alliance.
As Fiala said, "People have had enough of populists," and they want "normal, competent, and decent politics."
The opposition in Hungary will also create a unified electoral list for the parliamentary elections next year and field a single candidate for prime minister.
Of course, the Czech Republic still operates a democratic system, so Babiš is preparing to join the opposition forces.
However, toppling Putin is far more difficult, and it is not hard to predict that there will be more comprehensive measures aimed at crushing the Communist Party.
However, the above approach also brings risks to the Kremlin.
The current situation is that the president claims Russian democracy "has not died," pointing to the existence of an "active opposition" as evidence, indicating that he is at least still interested in pretending that Russia has not been driven toward near totalitarianism.
Putin says he only wants stability.
But his regime is pushing Russia toward a more turbulent situation.
If the Kremlin inconsistently formulates and implements rules against the Communist Party as it did with Russian liberals, driving the party underground, social explosion is more likely to occur.
And if it decides to stop repressing, the Russian communists — yes, the communists — could become a force that cannot be ignored.
